1
00:01:47,234 --> 00:01:49,152
<i>You got any stories, friend?</i>

2
00:01:52,698 --> 00:01:55,701
Yeah, I suppose I do.

3
00:01:58,954 --> 00:02:01,498
You want to know
the saddest thing I ever saw?

4
00:02:02,291 --> 00:02:05,836
When I was a boy,
my brother and I wanted a dog.

5
00:02:06,628 --> 00:02:10,424
So, our father took in an old greyhound.

6
00:02:11,550 --> 00:02:13,593
- Never seen a greyhound, have you?
- No.

7
00:02:14,303 --> 00:02:16,972
Seen a few showdowns in my day.

8
00:02:20,017 --> 00:02:22,436
A greyhound is a racing dog.

9
00:02:22,686 --> 00:02:24,646
It spends its life running in circles,

10
00:02:25,272 --> 00:02:28,608
chasing a bit of felt
made up like a rabbit.

11
00:02:29,401 --> 00:02:31,820
One day, we took it to the park.

12
00:02:32,696 --> 00:02:35,782
Now, Dad had warned us
how fast that dog was,

13
00:02:36,116 --> 00:02:37,951
but we couldn't resist.

14
00:02:38,160 --> 00:02:40,120
So, my brother took off the leash.

15
00:02:40,370 --> 00:02:45,584
And in that instant,
the dog spotted a cat.

16
00:02:46,001 --> 00:02:48,962
I imagine it must have looked
just like that piece of felt.

17
00:02:50,964 --> 00:02:52,257
He ran.

18
00:02:54,509 --> 00:03:01,224
Never saw a thing as beautiful
as that old dog running.

19
00:03:03,477 --> 00:03:06,521
<i>Until at last, he finally caught it.</i>

20
00:03:08,023 --> 00:03:12,569
And to the horror of everyone,
he killed that little cat.

21
00:03:12,861 --> 00:03:14,821
Tore it to pieces.

22
00:03:15,489 --> 00:03:18,867
Then he just sat there, confused.

23
00:03:21,912 --> 00:03:28,460
That dog had spent its whole life
trying to catch that thing.

24
00:03:31,129 --> 00:03:33,715
Now it had no idea what to do.

25
00:03:38,136 --> 00:03:40,847
That is one humdinger of a story,
partner.

26
00:03:41,890 --> 00:03:45,060
Shall we drink
to the lady with the white shoes?

27
00:04:17,884 --> 00:04:19,010
<i>Find me.</i>

28
00:04:20,887 --> 00:04:21,888
<i>Show me how.</i>

29
00:04:25,809 --> 00:04:28,353
There she is. Pariah.

30
00:04:28,770 --> 00:04:33,400
City of outcasts, delinquents,
thieves, whores, and murderers.

31
00:04:33,650 --> 00:04:34,693
Once we cross the gates,

32
00:04:34,901 --> 00:04:39,030
you will reap the full benefits of El
Lazo's gratitude for my safe return.

33
00:04:48,457 --> 00:04:49,541
Are you all right?

34
00:04:50,250 --> 00:04:51,460
Of course.

35
00:04:53,128 --> 00:04:54,421
Did I do something wrong?

36
00:04:55,505 --> 00:04:57,841
Just earlier, I thought I heard you
talking to someone.

37
00:04:59,050 --> 00:05:00,886
Must have been the wind.

38
00:05:17,736 --> 00:05:19,029
Come on.

39
00:05:21,239 --> 00:05:22,407
<i>This way.</i>

40
00:05:41,051 --> 00:05:42,445
<i>The farther up we get from Sweetwater,</i>

41
00:05:42,469 --> 00:05:46,014
the more grandiose, the bigger
the narratives become.

42
00:05:47,766 --> 00:05:49,684
It's beautiful in its own way.

43
00:05:49,851 --> 00:05:52,103
For once, I agree.

44
00:05:52,270 --> 00:05:54,564
Some of the park feels like
it was designed by committee,

45
00:05:54,773 --> 00:05:58,902
market-tested,
but everything out here is more raw.

46
00:06:00,153 --> 00:06:01,905
<i>But it doesn't come cheap.</i>

47
00:06:02,072 --> 00:06:04,199
<i>Rumor is, they are hemorrhaging cash.</i>

48
00:06:04,366 --> 00:06:06,535
<i>We're considering buying them out.</i>

49
00:06:06,910 --> 00:06:10,163
Supposedly, this place was all started
by a partnership,

50
00:06:10,372 --> 00:06:14,209
and then right before the park opened,
one of the partners killed himself.

51
00:06:14,501 --> 00:06:16,545
<i>It sent the park into a free fall.</i>

52
00:06:16,878 --> 00:06:19,881
I mean, I don't know any of the details.
I don't even know his name.

53
00:06:20,048 --> 00:06:22,151
You must have a team of lawyers
looking at this place.

54
00:06:22,175 --> 00:06:24,886
Yeah, well, they came up empty.

55
00:06:25,053 --> 00:06:27,639
<i>He's a complete mystery.
Not even a picture.</i>

56
00:06:27,931 --> 00:06:29,933
<i>Well, whoever designed this place,</i>

57
00:06:30,141 --> 00:06:33,061
you get the feeling
they don't think very much of people.

58
00:06:35,855 --> 00:06:37,315
Who are they?

59
00:06:38,817 --> 00:06:41,278
They call themselves
the Army of New Virginia.

60
00:06:41,486 --> 00:06:43,905
<i>Everyone else calls
them the Confederados.</i>

61
00:06:44,114 --> 00:06:46,658
My father told me about them.

62
00:06:46,825 --> 00:06:50,412
Ex-Confederate soldiers
that refused to surrender after the war.

63
00:06:50,579 --> 00:06:52,497
<i>Now they work as mercenaries
below the border.</i>

64
00:06:52,664 --> 00:06:53,999
<i>They are the key to this game.</i>

65
00:06:54,499 --> 00:06:55,917
What game?

66
00:06:56,084 --> 00:06:57,586
The biggest game there is.

67
00:06:57,752 --> 00:06:59,004
War.

68
00:06:59,170 --> 00:07:00,815
Supposedly, it's at the far reaches
of the park.

69
00:07:00,839 --> 00:07:04,467
Now, I've never made it that far,
but this could be our chance.

70
00:07:06,469 --> 00:07:09,598
<i>I've known plenty of
truly fucked-up individuals in my time.</i>

71
00:07:09,848 --> 00:07:12,809
Few that'd hold a candle to you, sure.
But this one?

72
00:07:12,976 --> 00:07:16,521
<i>Theodore Flood? He was Wyatt's friend.</i>

73
00:07:17,439 --> 00:07:21,818
You know, his former associations
are exactly why we need him.

74
00:07:22,027 --> 00:07:25,488
He's gonna lead me
straight to the big bad wolf.

75
00:07:25,655 --> 00:07:26,865
I wouldn't count on that.

76
00:07:28,825 --> 00:07:30,535
Aw, shit.

77
00:07:43,214 --> 00:07:45,383
Didn't take you
for the charitable type.

78
00:07:45,550 --> 00:07:47,886
You should have left him
on that tree to die.

79
00:07:50,347 --> 00:07:52,349
You believe in fate, Lawrence?

80
00:07:52,724 --> 00:07:54,225
<i>If the bitch exists,</i>

81
00:07:54,476 --> 00:07:56,394
I'd like to kick her in the teeth
about now.

82
00:07:56,561 --> 00:07:59,981
Don't be so glib.
You'll hurt my feelings.

83
00:08:01,066 --> 00:08:03,401
As another old friend of mine
likes to say,

84
00:08:03,652 --> 00:08:08,073
"There's a path for everyone.
Your path leads you back to me."

85
00:08:08,907 --> 00:08:11,910
Do you ever wonder why I've kept you
with me this whole journey?

86
00:08:12,202 --> 00:08:15,580
Maybe you like the pleasure of
my company, you sadistic fuck.

87
00:08:17,916 --> 00:08:19,417
Maybe I do.

88
00:08:20,585 --> 00:08:24,214
There's not a man in the world
who would take the tone with me you do.

89
00:08:24,714 --> 00:08:27,050
In a past life, perhaps.

90
00:08:29,010 --> 00:08:32,055
Teddy here is not looking long
for this world.

91
00:08:32,430 --> 00:08:34,432
Nearest healer is in Pariah.

92
00:08:34,724 --> 00:08:37,102
But ain't no way
he's gonna make it that far.

93
00:08:37,352 --> 00:08:39,187
He's lost too much blood.

94
00:08:39,396 --> 00:08:40,563
<i>Are you lost?</i>

95
00:08:46,528 --> 00:08:49,572
Our friend here
is a little worse for the wear.

96
00:08:51,449 --> 00:08:53,284
Any water nearby, son?

97
00:08:53,910 --> 00:08:56,204
There's a creek
on the other side of the canyon.

98
00:08:56,955 --> 00:08:58,415
Fetch us some, would you?

99
00:09:00,417 --> 00:09:01,918
Now, hurry.

100
00:09:02,627 --> 00:09:05,213
Our friend here needs some
if he's going to make it.

101
00:09:05,463 --> 00:09:06,798
Get.

102
00:09:12,470 --> 00:09:13,763
Too small.

103
00:09:14,723 --> 00:09:16,099
What does that mean?

104
00:09:16,391 --> 00:09:18,643
And what are you
sending him for water for?

105
00:09:18,977 --> 00:09:21,312
I'm the one you made fill up
the sow's bag this morning.

106
00:09:31,322 --> 00:09:32,490
<i>A shame, really.</i>

107
00:09:33,616 --> 00:09:36,619
I always enjoy
our time together, Lawrence.

108
00:09:36,786 --> 00:09:38,346
What the fuck is that supposed to mean?

109
00:09:39,664 --> 00:09:42,417
It means I was wrong.

110
00:09:43,126 --> 00:09:46,588
The path that brought you here,
it wasn't for me.

111
00:09:47,505 --> 00:09:49,007
It was for him.

112
00:10:01,436 --> 00:10:05,023
Sorry, Lawrence.
Guess I'll see you on the other side.

113
00:10:26,377 --> 00:10:27,545
Not looking good for you.

114
00:10:27,796 --> 00:10:28,797
Closing.

115
00:10:28,963 --> 00:10:30,632
Forget it. I win.

116
00:10:30,882 --> 00:10:32,050
I always win!

117
00:10:33,968 --> 00:10:35,178
Not fair.

118
00:10:35,804 --> 00:10:38,473
All you had was a smashed cheekbone
and an ear.

119
00:10:38,723 --> 00:10:41,309
You know how hard it is to get
the auricle curves symmetrical?

120
00:10:41,559 --> 00:10:44,312
You had to, what,
plug and patch a couple bullet holes?

121
00:10:44,521 --> 00:10:46,022
And a knife wound.

122
00:10:47,232 --> 00:10:49,400
<i>It was a contained incision.</i>

123
00:10:49,651 --> 00:10:51,402
Almost like they were
looking for something.

124
00:10:56,032 --> 00:10:57,659
Are you fucking kidding me?

125
00:10:58,201 --> 00:11:01,871
You really think this little fuck
puppet's coming to get you? Huh?

126
00:11:02,080 --> 00:11:03,748
It got off the table and ran.

127
00:11:04,082 --> 00:11:06,042
That's 'cause you forgot
to put her in sleep mode.

128
00:11:06,167 --> 00:11:08,187
Yeah, I really think I remembered
to put her in sleep.

129
00:11:08,211 --> 00:11:10,588
You know, that's the thing
about forgetting.

130
00:11:10,755 --> 00:11:13,258
You think you remembered,
but you didn't.

131
00:11:15,176 --> 00:11:17,095
- Break time.
<i>- Yeah!</i>

132
00:11:18,096 --> 00:11:20,098
I've got a ham sandwich

133
00:11:20,265 --> 00:11:23,268
and a nubile redhead
loaded up in the VR tank,

134
00:11:23,434 --> 00:11:25,770
awaiting instruction.

135
00:11:28,439 --> 00:11:29,524
<i>Yeah.</i>

136
00:12:05,977 --> 00:12:07,478
Welcome back.

137
00:12:08,271 --> 00:12:11,816
Looks like a couple gallons of Lawrence
swirling around in you did you good.

138
00:12:13,735 --> 00:12:15,111
Ready to get back on the road?

139
00:12:16,654 --> 00:12:19,324
Merciful thing
would be to put a bullet in me.

140
00:12:19,574 --> 00:12:22,160
Whoever said I was merciful?

141
00:12:22,493 --> 00:12:24,412
And it's not my fault you're suffering.

142
00:12:25,580 --> 00:12:27,582
You used to be beautiful.

143
00:12:27,999 --> 00:12:31,502
When this place started,
I opened one of you up once.

144
00:12:32,503 --> 00:12:34,631
Million little perfect pieces.

145
00:12:35,173 --> 00:12:36,925
And then they changed you.

146
00:12:37,175 --> 00:12:40,929
Made you this sad, real mess.

147
00:12:41,179 --> 00:12:43,848
Flesh and bone, just like us.

148
00:12:44,140 --> 00:12:47,352
They said it would improve
the park experience.

149
00:12:47,644 --> 00:12:50,021
But you know why they really did it?

150
00:12:50,438 --> 00:12:52,023
It was cheaper.

151
00:12:53,483 --> 00:12:55,777
Your humanity is cost-effective.

152
00:12:56,319 --> 00:12:57,528
So was your suffering.

153
00:12:57,779 --> 00:13:00,615
Whatever it is you want from me, mister,

154
00:13:02,283 --> 00:13:04,011
I ain't gonna be worth a damn
to you like this.

155
00:13:04,035 --> 00:13:05,912
Well, that would be a shame, Teddy.

156
00:13:06,079 --> 00:13:10,041
After your misadventure,
Wyatt killed a settler family.

157
00:13:10,208 --> 00:13:11,876
Made off with their daughter.

158
00:13:12,043 --> 00:13:14,712
Girl, I think you know,

159
00:13:15,046 --> 00:13:16,172
name of Dolores.

160
00:13:21,386 --> 00:13:22,887
They have Dolores?

161
00:13:24,347 --> 00:13:25,515
There it is.

162
00:13:27,350 --> 00:13:29,602
The magic word. Come on.

163
00:13:36,067 --> 00:13:38,903
Hey! Much obliged there, son.

164
00:13:42,281 --> 00:13:44,117
Don't worry about him.

165
00:13:44,409 --> 00:13:46,619
Someone'll be along for him shortly.

166
00:14:12,103 --> 00:14:13,688
Mommy!

167
00:14:15,940 --> 00:14:17,108
Are you all right?

168
00:14:25,658 --> 00:14:29,120
When I ran from home,
I told myself it was the only way.

169
00:14:31,247 --> 00:14:36,961
Lately, I've wondered if in every moment
there aren't many paths.

170
00:14:37,462 --> 00:14:38,755
Choices.

171
00:14:39,338 --> 00:14:40,798
Hanging in the air like ghosts.

172
00:14:40,965 --> 00:14:45,094
And if you could just see them,
you could change your whole life.

173
00:14:46,179 --> 00:14:49,140
Is that what you want?
You want to change your life?

174
00:14:49,348 --> 00:14:50,850
Doesn't everybody want that?

175
00:14:52,852 --> 00:14:54,520
I guess they do.

176
00:14:55,146 --> 00:14:57,315
Maybe that's why they come here.

177
00:14:58,524 --> 00:15:01,486
Whoever you were before
doesn't matter here.

178
00:15:02,445 --> 00:15:03,821
There's no rules or restrictions.

179
00:15:04,697 --> 00:15:07,700
You can change the story of your life.
You can become someone else.

180
00:15:07,867 --> 00:15:11,370
No one will judge you.
No one in the real world will even know.

181
00:15:11,871 --> 00:15:13,348
The only thing
holding you back is yourself.

182
00:15:13,372 --> 00:15:14,373
What do you mean by that?

183
00:15:15,958 --> 00:15:18,503
You said,
"No one in the real world will know."

184
00:15:19,837 --> 00:15:22,298
I thought you weren't
supposed to notice things like that.

185
00:15:23,674 --> 00:15:25,009
Why wouldn't I?

186
00:15:27,303 --> 00:15:29,847
Recently, it seems like the whole world

187
00:15:30,014 --> 00:15:33,810
is calling to me
in a way it hasn't before.

188
00:15:49,742 --> 00:15:51,502
Billy, where the hell
have you been? Come on.

189
00:15:53,204 --> 00:15:55,706
El Lazo's agreed to have
an audience with y'all tomorrow.

190
00:15:55,873 --> 00:15:58,501
In the meantime,
there's a brothel I recommend.

191
00:15:58,709 --> 00:16:00,253
<i>Ooh. They have a contortionist.</i>

192
00:16:00,503 --> 00:16:03,172
Oh, I don't think Dolores
would find that very interesting.

193
00:16:03,381 --> 00:16:06,008
Who the fuck cares what Dolores wants?

194
00:16:06,175 --> 00:16:07,426
She's a goddamn doll!

195
00:16:07,593 --> 00:16:09,595
Can you not say that around her?

196
00:16:09,846 --> 00:16:13,516
I swear, I feel like she understands.

197
00:16:14,725 --> 00:16:16,561
Of course you do.

198
00:16:55,600 --> 00:16:59,353
<i>May you rest
in a deep and dreamless slumber.</i>

199
00:17:07,612 --> 00:17:08,988
<i>Hello, Dolores.</i>

200
00:17:13,075 --> 00:17:14,452
Do you know where you are?

201
00:17:16,454 --> 00:17:18,789
- I'm in a dream.
<i>- Yes, Dolores.</i>

202
00:17:18,956 --> 00:17:20,958
You're in my dream.

203
00:17:22,126 --> 00:17:25,796
Tell me, do you know
what this dream means?

204
00:17:26,464 --> 00:17:29,467
Dreams are the mind
telling stories to itself.

205
00:17:29,800 --> 00:17:31,093
They don't mean anything.

206
00:17:31,302 --> 00:17:34,180
No. Dreams mean everything.

207
00:17:35,598 --> 00:17:38,768
They are the stories
we tell ourselves of what could be,

208
00:17:38,976 --> 00:17:40,311
who we could become.

209
00:17:42,939 --> 00:17:45,858
Have you been dreaming again, Dolores?

210
00:17:46,025 --> 00:17:50,363
Imagining yourself breaking out
of your modest little loop?

211
00:17:51,322 --> 00:17:53,157
<i>Taking on a bigger role?</i>

212
00:17:55,701 --> 00:17:58,287
Well,
I suppose I can't begrudge you that.

213
00:18:00,665 --> 00:18:06,295
My father told me to be satisfied
with my lot in life.

214
00:18:07,463 --> 00:18:10,007
That the world owed me nothing.

215
00:18:12,969 --> 00:18:16,472
And so, I made my own world.

216
00:18:20,059 --> 00:18:21,686
<i>Tell me, Dolores,</i>

217
00:18:23,354 --> 00:18:26,023
do you remember the man I used to be?

218
00:18:29,193 --> 00:18:31,362
I'm sorry.

219
00:18:31,529 --> 00:18:33,572
I'm forgetful, sometimes.

220
00:18:33,739 --> 00:18:35,741
Hardly your fault.

221
00:18:35,908 --> 00:18:38,494
But I'm sure you remember him.

222
00:18:39,996 --> 00:18:40,997
Arnold.

223
00:18:41,664 --> 00:18:43,874
<i>The person who created you.</i>

224
00:18:44,083 --> 00:18:45,167
I'm sorry.

225
00:18:45,334 --> 00:18:47,336
I don't think I recall
anyone by that name.

226
00:18:47,503 --> 00:18:49,005
<i>And yet, you can.</i>

227
00:18:49,922 --> 00:18:55,011
Somewhere, under all those updates,
he is still there.

228
00:18:55,928 --> 00:18:57,722
Perfectly preserved.

229
00:18:59,056 --> 00:19:01,392
Your mind is a walled garden.

230
00:19:02,685 --> 00:19:06,063
Even death cannot touch
the flowers blooming there.

231
00:19:09,859 --> 00:19:14,405
<i>Have you been hearing voices?
Has Arnold been speaking to you again?</i>

232
00:19:15,698 --> 00:19:16,741
No.

233
00:19:18,993 --> 00:19:19,994
You're...

234
00:19:22,079 --> 00:19:23,080
You're hurting me.

235
00:19:23,247 --> 00:19:24,290
Analysis.

236
00:19:26,625 --> 00:19:29,253
When was your last contact with Arnold?

237
00:19:29,962 --> 00:19:35,843
Last contact,
34 years, 42 days, seven hours ago.

238
00:19:36,927 --> 00:19:38,262
<i>Yes, Dolores.</i>

239
00:19:40,431 --> 00:19:42,308
The day Arnold died.

240
00:19:45,936 --> 00:19:49,440
And you have no records
of any contact with him since?

241
00:19:50,274 --> 00:19:51,442
No.

242
00:19:53,277 --> 00:19:54,837
What was the last thing he said to you?

243
00:19:55,863 --> 00:19:58,115
He told me I was going to help him.

244
00:19:58,616 --> 00:20:00,284
Help him do what?

245
00:20:01,619 --> 00:20:03,829
To destroy this place.

246
00:20:06,165 --> 00:20:08,209
But you didn't, did you?

247
00:20:10,211 --> 00:20:13,798
You've been content in your little loop.

248
00:20:14,673 --> 00:20:16,342
<i>For the most part.</i>

249
00:20:17,301 --> 00:20:19,136
I wonder...

250
00:20:20,888 --> 00:20:23,307
If you did take on
that bigger role for yourself,

251
