They have Logan.

504
00:44:42,306 --> 00:44:43,516
Help me.

505
00:44:44,267 --> 00:44:45,351
Help me.

506
00:44:48,604 --> 00:44:49,814
No.

507
00:44:54,610 --> 00:44:55,903
No more pretending.

508
00:45:07,290 --> 00:45:11,419
I thought you had no appetite
for war, boy.

509
00:45:11,711 --> 00:45:15,464
This is a declaration of war.

510
00:45:19,260 --> 00:45:20,720
El Lazo set us up.

511
00:45:20,970 --> 00:45:22,305
We can find him for you.

512
00:45:22,471 --> 00:45:25,600
You can find him for us
by joining him in hell.

513
00:45:29,604 --> 00:45:30,688
Dolores, run!

514
00:45:44,785 --> 00:45:45,912
Dolores?

515
00:45:59,634 --> 00:46:01,177
How did you do that?

516
00:46:01,844 --> 00:46:06,140
You said people come here
to change the story of their lives.

517
00:46:09,560 --> 00:46:12,730
I imagined a story
where I didn't have to be the damsel.

518
00:46:16,359 --> 00:46:19,612
Now that train is our only chance
of making it out of here alive.

519
00:46:52,812 --> 00:46:54,146
Motherfuckers.

520
00:47:07,743 --> 00:47:11,998
You pull that trigger,
we'll all go up in a ball of hellfire.

521
00:47:12,248 --> 00:47:14,417
So,
why don't you loosen your grip a mite?

522
00:47:22,425 --> 00:47:23,467
It's okay.

523
00:47:25,136 --> 00:47:26,262
I don't trust him.

524
00:47:26,429 --> 00:47:28,973
Which is the first step
to truly knowing me.

525
00:47:30,099 --> 00:47:31,767
Give me your gun, El Lazo.

526
00:47:37,648 --> 00:47:41,652
Now that we're all friends,
you can call me Lawrence.

527
00:47:42,653 --> 00:47:45,698
Now, why don't we settle in.
It's a long ride to the front.

528
00:47:57,334 --> 00:47:59,045
<i>You want a sip of this swill?</i>

529
00:48:03,466 --> 00:48:05,885
<i>Don't worry, it ain't nitro.</i>

530
00:48:14,310 --> 00:48:15,519
I'm coming.

531
00:48:36,248 --> 00:48:38,667
The girls are a little worn out,
but I can rouse one.

532
00:48:39,001 --> 00:48:40,377
You boys want some company?

533
00:48:40,544 --> 00:48:42,004
No. Just whiskey.

534
00:48:49,678 --> 00:48:52,848
Lawrence's donation must be running low.

535
00:48:53,682 --> 00:48:55,601
But we're short on time.

536
00:48:55,851 --> 00:48:57,603
You need to buck up, Teddy.

537
00:49:01,023 --> 00:49:03,359
<i>I told you, no company.</i>

538
00:49:04,902 --> 00:49:10,533
Thought I might join you, anyway,
as I never like to drink alone.

539
00:49:12,201 --> 00:49:15,913
Well, isn't this a rare honor?

540
00:49:17,039 --> 00:49:19,708
Teddy, you know who this is?

541
00:49:22,044 --> 00:49:23,629
Can't say that I do.

542
00:49:23,879 --> 00:49:26,715
Everything good
that has ever happened in your life,

543
00:49:26,924 --> 00:49:31,303
and everything rotten,
this is the man you have to thank.

544
00:49:34,890 --> 00:49:36,433
How am I doing, Robert?

545
00:49:37,476 --> 00:49:39,645
Any closer to finding
what I'm looking for?

546
00:49:39,812 --> 00:49:42,106
And what is that, exactly?

547
00:49:43,399 --> 00:49:45,234
<i>We're looking for a man named Wyatt.</i>

548
00:49:45,734 --> 00:49:49,071
Killed a rancher back in Sweetwater,
took his daughter.

549
00:49:51,574 --> 00:49:53,784
That last part doesn't sound familiar.

550
00:49:54,410 --> 00:49:57,371
Figured your stories
could use a little embellishment.

551
00:49:58,122 --> 00:50:02,251
You know, I always felt this place
was missing a real villain,

552
00:50:02,501 --> 00:50:05,421
hence my humble contribution.

553
00:50:07,256 --> 00:50:11,635
I admit, I lack the imagination
to even conceive of someone like you.

554
00:50:12,761 --> 00:50:15,848
The urgency, however,
doesn't quite fit the character.

555
00:50:16,432 --> 00:50:18,976
It betrays a certain anxiety.

556
00:50:21,729 --> 00:50:26,442
Now, Wyatt, on the other hand,
that's something new.

557
00:50:27,067 --> 00:50:30,279
Is he just another stooge for the
tourists to mount on their wall at home,

558
00:50:30,446 --> 00:50:33,282
or have you finally made
a worthy adversary?

559
00:50:34,742 --> 00:50:39,455
Someone to stop me
from finding the center of the maze.

560
00:50:41,332 --> 00:50:43,792
And what is it
you're hoping to find there?

561
00:50:46,962 --> 00:50:48,964
You know why you exist, Teddy?

562
00:50:50,007 --> 00:50:53,802
The world out there,
the one you'll never see,

563
00:50:54,803 --> 00:50:56,388
is one of plenty.

564
00:50:56,847 --> 00:50:59,975
A fat, soft teat
people cling to their entire life.

565
00:51:00,726 --> 00:51:03,395
Every need taken care of,

566
00:51:03,646 --> 00:51:04,813
except one.

567
00:51:06,148 --> 00:51:07,316
Purpose.

568
00:51:08,400 --> 00:51:09,652
Meaning.

569
00:51:10,527 --> 00:51:12,321
So, they come here.

570
00:51:12,488 --> 00:51:15,074
They can be a little scared,
a little thrilled,

571
00:51:15,241 --> 00:51:17,326
enjoy some sweetly affirmative bullshit,

572
00:51:17,493 --> 00:51:20,537
and then they take a fucking picture
and they go back home.

573
00:51:21,830 --> 00:51:25,209
But I think there's a deeper meaning

574
00:51:25,376 --> 00:51:27,503
hiding under all that.

575
00:51:27,836 --> 00:51:32,216
Something that the person
who created it wanted to express.

576
00:51:35,344 --> 00:51:37,137
Something true.

577
00:51:39,139 --> 00:51:41,850
Well, if you're looking
for the moral of the story,

578
00:51:42,017 --> 00:51:43,310
you could quite simply ask.

579
00:51:43,727 --> 00:51:46,021
I'd need a shovel.

580
00:51:46,188 --> 00:51:49,233
The man I'd be asking died 35 years ago.

581
00:51:49,483 --> 00:51:51,402
Almost took this place with him.

582
00:51:51,652 --> 00:51:55,197
Almost, but not quite. Thanks to me.

583
00:51:55,864 --> 00:51:59,034
Well, maybe he left something behind.

584
00:52:01,870 --> 00:52:06,083
I wonder what I would find
if I opened you up.

585
00:52:14,550 --> 00:52:18,887
Even at death's door,
you're still a loyal pet.

586
00:52:26,270 --> 00:52:27,980
Is that why you came here, Robert?

587
00:52:29,106 --> 00:52:31,066
To try to talk me out of it?

588
00:52:31,483 --> 00:52:33,402
On the contrary.

589
00:52:33,986 --> 00:52:38,407
Far be it from me to get in the way
of a voyage of self-discovery.

590
00:52:49,960 --> 00:52:51,211
Mr. Flood.

591
00:52:51,378 --> 00:52:56,800
We must look back and smile
at perils past, mustn't we?

592
00:53:09,063 --> 00:53:12,900
We should get back on the road.
Time's a-wasting.

593
00:55:06,054 --> 00:55:07,556
<i>Hello, Felix.</i>

594
00:55:11,226 --> 00:55:13,604
It's time you and I had a chat.

